-- 
Crude, Heating Oil, Gasoline Gain on Confidence: Oil Products

-- B y   R i c h a r d   S t u b b e
-- 
2011-04-15T20:16:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-15/crude-heating-oil-gasoline-gain-on-confidence-oil-products.html
Crude oil , heating oil, and
gasoline rose more than 1 percent as better-than-forecast U.S.
consumer confidence and industrial data bolstered optimism in
the economy of the world’s biggest crude-consuming country.
Ethanol declined.  Futures increased after the Thomson Reuters/University of
Michigan April preliminary index of consumer sentiment advanced
to 69.6 from 67.5 the prior month. The  Federal Reserve  said U.S.
production at factories rose 0.8 percent in March, the fifth
straight gain.  Crude Oil  Crude oil for May delivery gained $1.55, or 1.4 percent, to
$109.66 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange , closing
the week with a decline of 2.8 percent. Prices are up 28 percent
this year.  “Today’s numbers show that the  U.S. economy  is rebounding
strongly,” said Jason Schenker, president of Prestige
Economics, an energy advisory firm in Austin,  Texas . “The
global economic recovery is still on track despite high oil
prices.”  Gasoline  Gasoline for May delivery rose 5.45 cents, or 1.7 percent,
to $3.2892 a gallon on the Nymex, ending the week with a gain of
0.9 percent, the fourth consecutive weekly increase. Gasoline
has increased 41 percent in a year.  Regular gasoline at the pump, averaged nationwide,
increased 0.3 cent to $3.815 a gallon yesterday, AAA said on its
website. The price, which AAA tracks seven days a week, has
advanced every day since March 21.  Heating Oil  Heating oil for May delivery rose 3.52 cents, or 1.1
percent, to $3.2242 a gallon, ending the week with a decline of
2.9 percent. Heating oil has gained 43 percent in a year.  Ethanol  Denatured ethanol for May delivery dropped for the fourth
straight day, falling 2.1 cents, or 0.8 percent, to $2.618 a
gallon on the Chicago Board of Trade. Ethanol has increased 66
percent in the past year.  Refineries and Transport  Total SA (FP)  plans to remove equipment from service to repair a
leak at its Port Arthur refinery in Texas, according to a filing
with state regulators. Workers isolated an exchanger that
appears to be leaking process fluid into a heat-exchange system,
the company said in a filing with the Texas Commission on
Environmental Quality.  Exxon Mobil Corp. (XOM)  said all units continue to operate after
a breakdown caused emissions at its Torrance, California,
refinery.  To contact the reporter on this story:
